Great neighborhood pharmacy near Woodland Hills area, located in West Hills! Very friendly and helpful staff, and Robert is always a pleasure to speak with when needing my scripts filled. This pharmacy is like the old days of local ones in your neighborhood, where they offered better overall service compared to the large chains. I would prefer supporting a small local business whenever possible. They are worth the switch from the typical pharmacies!</Text>

< review>
Saw that this was a little different than other Mexican restaurants. They offer typical dishes from Oaxaca. I shared the alebrije supreme. It was pretty darn good! It came with 2 sopes (not too different from other Mexican restaurants), 2 molotes (never had or seen on another mexican menu), and 3 empanadas.  I believe what the empanadas are stuffed with is authentic Oaxacan ingredients. DELICIOUS! I look forward to trying other dishes here.</review>

My 5-year old son and I went to Simpkins for the first time this past Saturday, and were duly impressed. There are different swim sessions open to different age/skill groups, so that was great for us as my son is just learning to swim, and would be distracted if older kids were in the pool with him. In "open swim", on certain weekend times, only kids 6 and under are allowed, which was perfect for us.

There are life guards at every pool/area, and they're very attentive, and we felt safe. The facilities were clean, the staff friendly, and prices reasonable ($6 for me and $4 for my son). We will definitely be going back soon.< /review>

<Review>There's a pretty big selection of a wide variety of styles here, and it is always clean and usually fairly well organized. Prices are great. The staff are friendly and happy to help if asked, but not in your face. I will say, however, that this is not the place to go if you are bigger than a size Large (hence the deduction of 1 star). They have a HUGE selection in XS and S, and a good selection in M and L, but I only saw a couple of items in XL.

I started shopping here when I was 19 and unfortunately, I am either aging or of their core demographic (I'm 31 now), or I am just really not into the current trends of crop tops, off the shoulder tops, and distressed tees (the first 2 of which are not functional for the mother of an active toddler). I'm a mechanic myself , and my experience with John is such undescribable. I'd totally recommend John for anyone who's looking for used cars with in their budget that goes along with top-notch service.</review>

I have lived in luxury apartments as well as low level apartments before. This apartment is not cheap and there are things that I am not happy about this building.
1- It is right on the highway, even though my apartment is in the middle of the building, I can still hear all the highway noise very much, specially in early morning when I need very quiet time for sleep.
2- There are mandatory charge for internet and TV package, which I do not use TV at all. This is not acceptable.
3- The walls are so thin you could hear the slightest music. My neighbors are banging on the walls all the time for those who have any music going.
4- Pool is 3 feet deep, which is very shallow, it should have been at least 3'6". I was hoping that my daughter can learn how to swim, but with very shallow pool, it is not possible.
5-The closet in the second bedroom is so small
6- One side of the building does not get sun light at all and is very dark, so make sure, pay attention to that.
7- The hard wood flooring are not very tight, and are noisy
8- One bathroom has no tub in the 2 bedroom and only head shower.
9- I have to pay extra for the second car parking. If I have 2 bedroom I expected to have 2 car parking. It is not even reserved and $75 is not cheap.
10- Outside is a commercial area only, no residential, so if you like it, its ok.

Chelsey and Ben are very quick to respond and nice, but the policy is not changing.<//Text>

I absolutely love living at The Ellington in Pasadena, California!  These apartments are beautiful as they're newly constructed with a sleek and modern feel.  The community is one of the best I've ever been a part of.  Management is friendly and takes care of residents as well as their needs in a timely manner.  Maintenance responds to order requests quickly and ensure quality work.  It has a thriving warm community and is dog/family friendly.  The central location of The Ellington is crucial. Their amenities are also very attractive: a fitness center, swimming pool + cabanas, outdoor fire place, BBQ grills and courtyard + corn holes.  I am stoked to be living here and to be a part of this community!</Text>

<Rating>4<//Rating>< Review>
I downsized from a house with a pool and thought this place would be temporary; however, it has been so convenient to markets, metro, 210 fwy, restaurants; and now I am enjoying NOT dealing with a house, yard, maintenance etc.   I do not recommend this place for families with young children (4 to 12) because it is mostly young professionals, single units, bachelors (etts), or families with babies (ie don't need a yard).    That being said; it is great for couples or single people as it has a pool, BBQ, community room, conference room etc.    East Pasadena is a great place to live and it does not have nearly as much traffic as the Westside or OC.     You get 1 parking spot for a 1 bedroom; and $75.00 extra for each extra auto.   Also, you can rent storage space if you need it.

The place is new; management is on top of things; and it is safe and clean.   For apartment living; it gets high marks; and the tenants community always seems nice and respectful.</Review>

Burgers are always good, but...
Coworkers and I just got them for lunch. I was sitting right next to my coworker when she called in the order. Two barbeque burgers, one with cheddar, one with pepper jack, and a 5 item salad. When I got there, they had for some reason added a side salad, but they took it off so whatever. Then after I paid I saw the receipt said American cheese on both burgers. I told the guy working that it was supposed to be 1 pepper jack one cheddar, and he said it was just that way on the tag, but the burgers should have the right cheese. They were both American, and they forgot the dressing on the salad. Pretty basic stuff to mess up. Also they didn't ask if I wanted ketchup but whatever some places don't do that. 0/3 on this order. So I guess if you eat here just make sure they get your order right. Otherwise it's really good food< /text>

<Name>LaToya Ross<//Name><date>1625449566372<//date>< rating>
5< /rating>
<review>In February, I lost my father unexpectedly and I had no clue where to begin to prepare a funeral. The Long Beach VA provided me with a booklet of mortuaries to call.  I called so many and it seemed like no one had capacity. I called McKenzie Mortuary and received a return call from the owner, Ken that eased my heart.

Ken was very kind and understanding. He understood my father was a Army Veteran who passed at the VA hospital and how important it was to have him receive a dignified service.  Ken sat down with me to create a wonderful Veterans package. He connected my family with Pastor Brown and the most amazing video creator Dave. Dave's slide show of my dad's life was AMAZING and it made my family remember all the good times with dad and cry tears of joy.

I am thankful for the wonderful staff at McKenzie's mortuary. And for Ken taking time to return my call and allowing my father to have the most beautiful funeral services. Thank you.< /review>< Pics>

< Name>
Sean Gonzales< /Name>
<Text>VERY VERY DISAPPOINTED ON THEIR CUSTOMER SERVICE SKILL. (Lack of)

I rushed from work to make it to Vroman's Before their closing time, which was 6 o'clock this Friday night. I had to buy a Birthday gift from their stationary department. A Mont Blanc Pen to be exact.

I made it by 5:58 2 minutes shy of their closing time thinking I would be able to get in. Needless to find out the doors were prematurely locked before 6 o'clock.

As I knocked through the glass door, as I am staring at a sign right infront of me saying 6 o'clock is closing time, as I point my iPhone through the glass door, that reads 5:58.

2 ladies behind the cash register are counting the cash behind the register. I knock on the door saying it's before 6 o'clock (2 minutes, I know its not much, but still they shouldn't lock the doors before 6 if that is what the sign says)

One lady in her late fifties/ealrly sixties with long brown hair and glasses approached the door and said we are closed talking behind the door. I showed her my iPhone screen saying its not 6 pm yet, and I need 1 minute to buy a pen.

She said sorry, I can't help you we close at 6. I showed her the time, clearly not 6 o'clock yet, and she said her time says different on the watch. Really? Your time on your wrist watch or on the wall may be ahead a few minutes, you may want to fix that as the time on the iPhone is more accurate.

She wouldn't care less that they had closed the store sooner than what they had shown/listed on the door. she nodded her head saying sorry, try back next week as we are extending our hours to a later time and that she would share the time issue with management. Really? Are you stupid or what? You see the time on the iPhone as I showed you, and your iPhone (if you have an iPhone or any phone reads the same)

I did not rush through traffic to make it before your closing time, for you to tell me to come back next Friday with extended hours, when you should be open until 6pm.

I was getting ready to buy a Mont Blanc Pen from their stationary department, as I have purchased several from the past, and have spent at least $5000 dollars on Mont Blanc pens at the store.

They say support your neighborhood book store, but not with this kind of lack of empathy and laziness and lies, when they list they will close at 6 pm and they close sooner without a care, and a cold stare/look.

There are many many other places I can spend my money, and I will no longer support you and your business. Just few months ago I purchased a limited Edition Disney Mont Blanc Pen set for almost $1000. This will be my last time. (see photos)

You really need to have people that care to be there, want to work there, and some sense of logic and common sense. If the phone screen is showing that the time is 5:58 and the closing time says is 6 pm. GUESS WHAT? CLOSING TIME IS 6 not 5:55, 5:56, 5:57, 5:58, or even 5:59 etc...

SO SO DISAPPOINTED as I had been a customer for over 20 years. Keep hiring employees at this low level caliber who don't give a single C R A P, then you are not going to last much longer, as I can easily shop at AMAZON.<//Text>< resp>
{'time': 1614906848135, 'text': 'Our sincere apologies for this unfortunate interaction and thank you for taking the time to bring it to our attention.  It is absolutely understandable that you were taken aback at the way this was handled in light of our mistake in closing the doors early.  Instead of finding a way to accommodate your request to make a quick purchase of an item you knew you wanted we suggested you return another day and dug our heals into the fact that the store was closed (early!).  We have already used your experience as a training opportunity to not only amplify why it is so important to find a way to say yes to our customers, but ultimately to be better and always strive to ensure the we are providing our very best customer service in every situation.\nWe sincerely hope that you will consider giving us another chance and that you will visit us again.'}</resp>

< Review>
I really believe that majority of the people here do not like their jobs, I know that COVID-19 has everyone frazzled and I typically don't really review spots. I went to grab a book for a friend that was stuck in traffic (and we thought hey let's support a local business). I was greeted with a "we close in 10 minutes". Awesome I already have a book on hold I just want to pay for it. I'm then informing the employee that I've never been here before, I got shuffled around and interacted with 6 different people only one was pleasant. I understand it's a long day but I wholeheartedly believe if I was white these interactions would not have been so nonchalant as if I was inconveniencing them. I should've saved my time and spent my money on Amazon. Do better.</Review>

<rating>5< /rating><review>I have been going here for years; I love the place. It's one of the only independent bookstores in the area these days for good reason. The staff are very helpful and knowledgeable, with great recommendations.

For those wondering, they have taken prudent COVID-19 measures (mask requirement, enforcing social distancing, sanitizer, one way in and out, etc.) The entrance is in the back exclusively during altered operation and there is often a line to get in (but it moves fast!) Definitely check this place out of you are looking for a new read. The cafe has some pretty tasty treats as well, and a well-stocked newsstand right next door.< /review><pictures>None</pictures>< Resp>

<Resp>None< /Resp><review>I made my second visit to 1894 today at about the same time as last week: the result was like the difference between night and day. Yes the main Bartender was  someone different, Barry.  And i'm thinking that this is why the adherence to good service was so much better than last week.
To be fair at 12-ish it was pretty slow and there was no sudden influx of about 15 customers as there was last week. I  would say that you can look at this two ways: one...people were turned off with the bad or inept service last week or two: business was geared to arrive later today based on any number of factors.
In any event: Barry's service was on point and contributed greatly to a pleasant early afternoon visit.
I ordered:
a flight of Chardonnay: both oaked and unoaked
an order of flavored popcorn
a 3 cheese plate of Brie, Lavender cheddar and smoked gouda
Mixed Nuts as in last week
glass of Pinot Noir
The Chard selections are interesting but the San Simeon from Monterey County was Oaky, fruity with earthy notes and the winner as far as i am concerned. The flight selection is interesting: going from non-oaked (grassy, light, notes of apple though w/o too much body), "lightly' oaked (more interesting than the non oak as the chard grape in my book blossoms in oak casks adding deep tones of pepper, citrus and even melon) and heavily oaked (robust, cherries and pecan tones).
The Cheese plate is iffy as the cheeses were variable in quality and taste with the Brie winning the horse race after i asked Marcus to mildly nuke it for 8 seconds.  Cold Brie is w/o taste. Room temp or heated Brie is much better.The plate also comes with tasty olives and gigantic capers. The crackers served were average though i would have preferred bread. And where is the spread as in mustard?
The Nuts as in last week are a bargain at 5 bucks and feature the good stuff: macadamia, pecans, walnuts plus)
All-in-all a much better visit than last week due to the positivism and personality of Barry and chill personality of Marcus. But the food selections are an issue as is the plating/presentation on the several that i have ordered particularly the cheese plate.
I did have a chance to speak to the GM, Bentley about  wine, food, She is a positive person who seems like someone who is looking to improve amd open to suggestions.
Since this place is inside Vroman's and next door to the Laemmle Movie theater, i will definitely be back.
Cheers!</review><gmap_id>0x80c2c3680468043b:0x9085cc0a2f1ed3d1</gmap_id><Name>Mccauley Rocha</Name>< Pictures>

< review>
Vroman's Newstand is indeed still open! Though the stand has been reduced to a smaller but manageable left-side area, they still have their unmatched selection of news/magazine selections.

If you don't see the newspaper/magazine you're looking for at first glance, then do ask -  it's possibly hidden beneath other publications and not fanned out due to space restrictions. I was able to find everything I was looking for, including an obscure science mag that probably has a readership of a dozen people. Their staff are incredibly knowledgeable and will instantly know what you're looking for! (I mean, I've never ever had a book question these guys can't answer. Vroman's book peeps are amazing. They're superhuman!).

Thanks to Vroman's for the stand. It's just priceless to still be able to get paper copies of the Times, LA Times, etc.

COVID safety note: I am very careful and have not ventured into any commercial establishments through this whole pandemic. I do however feel safe going to the Vroman's Newstand as it's fully outdoors, and you can even stand in the sun, no less. If you're concerned about the safety of staff/yourself, I think you can feel pretty good about visiting the stand.<//review>

Vroman's NEVER disappoints!  I love supporting my not-so-local bookstore.  I purchased three magazines, two boxes of Christmas cards and two Christmas books (Christmas items were 50% off), three children's books, a young adult novel, and a graphic novel. <Review>The best not-really-a-book-store in LA. They not only cater to book lovers but also to lovers of book lovers. A 'stuff' shop first and foremost and the best place to get fountain pens or notebooks in greater Los Angeles. They recently opened a bar inside and have a lovely little coffee shop too. If I lived nearby I would probably forego rent and just wait for opening and live inside.

Their book selection is wonderful, but there is no chance at used books here. However, there are plenty of true bookstores nearby with fewer knickknacks and more dusty tomes.

It's not hard to convince someone to spend an hour at Vroman's. It earns it's tenuous spot at five stars but holds steady for now. My hope is they pull from Powell's and work out a used book strategy in order to become the mega-store they so rightly deserve to be.</Review><Time>1582588325342< /Time>< user_id>

<rate>5<//rate>< text>
I have been going to this store for years. One of my greatest pleasures is just browsing their book displays and all the fun stuff they have on both floors, from soaps to Christmas decorations to fine stationery. Recently, I wanted something unusual: a book for a person who is still learning English. The salesperson, Joy, after listening carefully to my needs, took me to 2 separate places in the store to find books on learning English and on writing. After she left me, she was helping another person with a completely different esoteric question -- I think on female jazz artists. Wow.  In addition, they now have a Jones Coffee cafe on the premises, and some dudes playing on a beat-up piano outside. It's a fine bookstore!</text>

This is one of the oldest bookstore around that I know of. Considering its size it's impressively well stocked. I rarely have issues finding a book here (unless it's so obscure that no book store would carry it). It's always clean, tidy, and organized. The atmosphere is always quite comfortable. < user>
111145999662976762686</user>
< Name>
Ardyss Hawley< /Name>
<Date>1582044577177< /Date>< rate>
4</rate>
< Text>
Vrooman's is the type of bookstore that when you walk in, you may be reminded of Barnes & Nobles; honestly, I wouldn't blame you if the thought crossed your mind, given the unexpected largeness of the shop, expansive book selection, and of course the classic coffee bar and wine bar (Yes, they have a wine bar!). Independent bookstores usually can't do what Vrooman's does.

The truth is: those other big bookstore chains wish they could be more like Vrooman's. At other stores, their largeness feels empty. Meanwhile at Vrooman's, it's a thrilling hunt for some quirky find -- a book or perhaps from one of the themed displays littered across the store. Book browsers (and gift givers), welcome to your new home of discovery. Whether you want to wander into a new genre without a clue (my usual choice for a day at Vrooman's) or seek out a newly released novel, they will likely have what you want or a worthy recommended staff pick. I like to explore the twists and turns of the aisles just to read the recommendations! Despite how popular and busy Vrooman's always is, the aisles never feel crowded. Make sure you check upstairs, especially the always changing art (available for purchase) in the staircase, and return later for an author talk or book fair; many talks are hosted up here or in the courtyard.

As for their coffee and wine bar, I've yet to order from either. If it's anything like the rest of Vrooman's, they probably serve "the good stuff," and I really hope so, because anything less would be a big let down. Unlike the rest of Vrooman's, the coffee shop has always been too crowded for me. All I can say is good luck getting a seat. Maybe the best time to visit is right at opening. Wine at nine, anyone?<//Text>

<Name>Polly Geller<//Name>< user>
101711425326703573962</user>
<text>If you don't know who bought Book Soup in WeHo, you do now: Vroman's. Pasadena's very own oldest indie bookstore, over 150 years old.
They offer educators a wee discount on materials used in classrooms. Their book signing series is outstanding. And the staff... Absurdly brilliant. From the knowledgeable Fountain pen Heads who know their inks and bobs down pat, to the  informative staff - I mean, I don't know when I last had a conversation that was worthy of a college level course on 13th century middle East philosophy and the humanities. On HIS lunch break. Who does that???? Unless they genuinely love where they work, n'est-ce-pas? Hail to the Holy Grale that is Vroman's. Order a cup of Joe from Jones Coffee Roasters while there. And if you need to find a gift, look no further. Their pet-related miscellany, their stationery, and their mugs! Too perfectly curated. L'Chaim!<//text>< Time>

< text>
The hands down, thumbs up best bookstore in Pasadena, maybe the San Gabriel Valley, and top 5 in the Los Angeles metro area.  There is a nice coffee shop in front.  Out on the street there is a good news stand.  Upstairs there is an excellent kids section and a separate area for cards and gifts.  I like the staff recommendations.  The cards that the staff write usually inspire me to pick up a book.  Very large fiction section.  Great atmosphere.  If you like bookish things, Vromans is certainly worth your time.</text>

<name>Brett Bernath</name><Time>1514438882445<//Time><Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
The hands down, thumbs up best bookstore in Pasadena, maybe the San Gabriel Valley, and top 5 in the Los Angeles metro area.  There is a nice coffee shop in front.  Out on the street there is a good news stand.  Upstairs there is an excellent kids section and a separate area for cards and gifts.  I like the staff recommendations.  The cards that the staff write usually inspire me to pick up a book.  Very large fiction section.  Great atmosphere.  If you like bookish things, Vromans is certainly worth your time.< /review>

This independent bookseller has been around for over a hundred years now. The redesign over the last decade was a welcomed addition, but now we're at a point where it feels like home. This is a great place to not only pick up books but meet authors. It seems like they are there almost daily. From independent presses to mainstream novels, this is a great spot to read a book, pick up a new one, and chat with the most knowledgeable staff in town.</Review>

<username>Linda Brumfield</username>< Review>
I ordered two different books at the Hastings Ranch Store two weeks ago. I never received a phone call. After one week,  I went to the store. They had one of the books. I waited another week and went back to the store for the second book. They did not have it. When I became persistent, they called the store in Pasadena. The store in Pasadena said they did not have it but they had a shipment that had not been opened. I was persistent again and another person called again to the Pasadena store, and they found 2 copies of the book. I drove to the Pasadena store, and THEY could not find it. After being persistent again and waiting for a long time, and talking to a manager, THEY FOUND TWO COPIES OF THE BOOK! I could have ordered it on Amazon and received it the next day and for allot cheaper! It‚Äôs unfortunate that Vromans is the only bookstore in town! I will never go there again. They didn‚Äôt offer to compensate me for my hardship, with a coupon or discount or something! Do not order anything from Vromans! Order from Amazon. After all of that, today I got a call from Hastings Ranch to tell me that my book was there! Go figure...</Review>

< review>
I ordered two different books at the Hastings Ranch Store two weeks ago. I never received a phone call. After one week,  I went to the store. They had one of the books. I waited another week and went back to the store for the second book. They did not have it. When I became persistent, they called the store in Pasadena. The store in Pasadena said they did not have it but they had a shipment that had not been opened. I was persistent again and another person called again to the Pasadena store, and they found 2 copies of the book. I drove to the Pasadena store, and THEY could not find it. After being persistent again and waiting for a long time, and talking to a manager, THEY FOUND TWO COPIES OF THE BOOK! I could have ordered it on Amazon and received it the next day and for allot cheaper! It‚Äôs unfortunate that Vromans is the only bookstore in town! I will never go there again. They didn‚Äôt offer to compensate me for my hardship, with a coupon or discount or something! Do not order anything from Vromans! Order from Amazon. After all of that, today I got a call from Hastings Ranch to tell me that my book was there! Go figure...<//review>

< review>
Vroman's is absolutely amazing and very well worth visiting...
Surprisingly large inside they have a section to cover every possible interest. The huge selection of books is almost overwhelming and yet always satisfying. The store is always neatly organized and extremely clean. The employees are always very friendly and ready to answer questions.
This isn't just a bookstore though, they also have an entire section of high quality writing utensils, planners/organisers, desktop trinkets and other small items that can be paired with a book to make the perfect gift.
This is the kind of store you can literally get lost in for a couple hours or more.< /review>

<review>Very cool bookstore in Pasadena.  It is the oldest and largest independent bookstore in Southern California and has been a Pasadena staple since 1894, I believe.  There are lots of nooks and crannies for you to squirrel yourself away and review a book you're thinking about buying and they have a grand selection, some available with employee book reviews to help you with your decision.  There is also a coffee shop indoors and they carry many decor and personal use items which make great gifts for your loved ones or even yourself.  I can get lost in this store for hours just "window shopping", lol.</review>< Pictures>

< text>
Beautiful bookstore, I wish there were more of these around. Hopefully this one doesn't go any time soon! I really like the personalized mini book recommendations provided by the staff throughout the store!

< Text>
Love this historic book store! Great children's section, focused sections on art/ feminism/American immigrants and resistance. Fun, sometimes kitchy gifts that are a treat to look at. Quiet, and no one will bother you.  Lots of literary gifts, and an awesome selection of recommendations by the staff - who are super friendly. A bit too much trendy, national brand soap/lotion/candle stock for sale on the second floor for an Indy book shop, but you gotta make money somehow, right? Definitely stop in. Then go to Amara Cafe and Chocolate for the best churros and award winning chocolate con leche.< /Text>

<userid>115581741580011137066< /userid>< user_name>
Alec Fredericks< /user_name>
< Time>
1479663330727<//Time>
<Rate>5< /Rate><text>Browns is proof positive that bookstores are still relevant in the days of digital consumption. With two floors of perfectly organised books and a smattering of knickknacks, you will immediately be put in the mood to browse and discover.

The children's book section is where my family always ends up and both of my kids learned to read from books are Vroman's. It's also a great environment to hang out to read to your kids.

Vroman's also has many special events, from book signings to weekly story time. They're always really well organized and engaging.

The newest attraction for me is the addition of The Next Chapter coffee shop, which is operated by the folks who run Jones Coffee in Pasadena. It's a nice atmosphere with a good amount of outdoor seating to enjoy the great coffee and the occasional pastry.

Vroman's isn't just a neighborhood bookstore, it's a destination. With everything it offers and all of the local restaurants nearby, you could find yourself spending the entire day, and you'd be better for it.< /text>< Pictures>

< review>
Excellent bookstore but full price on all things. Vroman's is an institution in Pasadena. They do not buy old books. There are two locations: In Pasadena location there is a smallish coffee bar attached to store. It is right next door to the Laemmle movie house. The Hastings Ranch store is much smaller in same strip mall as Whole Foods. There is a Starbucks just across from it. Excellent service at both locations.<//review>

< Text>
Vromans is amazing...I've been a patron for more than 20 years! Author events with the fine caliber of authors are superb as well as the events they have been presenting for children for years! It is rare that I visit Vromans for less than 90 minutes!< /Text>

115361046958967719736< /UserId.>
<Name>Lindsay Dennis< /Name><Date>1506383995394</Date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< review>
One of the last independent bookstore's remaining. Incredible  authors come to Vroman's, read from their novels, sign their books for fans and answer questions from fans. I had the opportunity to see Chuck Palahniuk and participate in the hijinks and fun atmosphere he created. He signed one of my favorite books. Events like this occur frequently and all you need to do is sign up for their newsletter to find out when.

Vroman's selection is huge and if they don't have your book, they'll order it for you.

Amazon is great for lots of things but not for independent bookstores. Support your local bookstores and if you're in the Los Angeles area, Vroman's is a must experience.<//review>

< Rate>
4<//Rate>
< Text>
I mourned the day Open Vroman's Bookstore abandoned its River North locale for greener pastures. What used to be just down the street, was now  by car. A tote in hand and some cash, I decided to make the pilgrimage on foot. Not much has changed cosmetically in the newer space-- similar exposed loft interiors with all the same furniture. It definitely feels more warehouse than homey bookstore. I do miss all the windows from their former location. Back then, it seemed they couldn't cram enough books onto their shelves. Here, it seemed all of them had room to breathe. New reads and revs, fiction, poetry,<//Text>

One of the best bookstores in SoCal. It's not Powell's but it's a reader's dream in Pasadena. They often have author signings. There's coffee on premises, too. It's a beautiful space. Lots of staff recommendations, if that's your thing. It's a Pasadena treasure.< /Review>

<user>107919054978557412146<//user><Name>Brian Cooper<//Name><date>1352961311961<//date>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< review>
I grew up on Vroman's Book Store, my grandmother worked their for 30+ Years and I remember getting to go through the stacks to find her when ever we came in, and she was not in sight out front.  This is where I developed my strong love of reading and why I still like paper over digital for reading.  I have the digital but certain books not only need to be read, but felt (texture of the page) scent of the paper, and sound turning the page makes can not be replaced.  It all helps to increase the imagination as I troll through the authors world.  I can sometimes even remember the scent of some of the women's perfume when I think of some of the times I was their. Of course I also have my special books grandma always brought home for me when I need the next one in a Science fiction series that I could not do with out. ( Usually Star Trek ).  The area has changed the block has changed the look of the street has changed.

Vroman's Book Store quality and customer service has not.  Keep it up guys and enjoy the Holiday's.

Brian<//review>

Like a high-brow Barnes and Noble. In the best imaginable way.

COFFEE
B&N: "Starbucks"
Vroman's: Pasadena's excellent independent roaster, Jones'

BOOKS
B&N: Every bestseller, except the one you wanted
Vroman's: Every bestseller, plus beautifully curated employee picks and entire sections that would never make it into B&N

STUFF
B&N: Moleskin notebooks, cheap book lights
Vroman's: Tons of notebooks, gorgeous stationary, pens of all budgets, tons and tons of gifts for book and culture lovers, everything you could ever want -- please let me live there, please; just let me pitch a tent between fiction and philosophy -- I won't make much noise, I won't start any trouble, just give me a couple of cortados a day, I -- I know you close at 11 -- yes, I know it's 11:30, but -- okay, okay, I'm going -- don't -- don't threaten me with Kant's complete works -- I'm going!
